# Routing — how packets find their way

Sending to `93.184.216.34`? The kernel checks its **routing table** for which interface + next hop to use, picking the **most specific** match.

```bash
ip route
```

```
default via 192.168.1.1 dev eth0
192.168.1.0/24 dev eth0 src 192.168.1.42
```

- **`default via 192.168.1.1`** — anything unmatched goes to the **default gateway** (the router / cloud virtual gateway).
- **`192.168.1.0/24 dev eth0`** — the local network is **directly attached**, no gateway needed.

Most machines have exactly these two: **local is direct, everything else via the gateway.**

## Change & debug

```bash
sudo ip route add 10.0.0.0/8 via 192.168.1.254   # temporary
ip route get 8.8.8.8      # which interface + gateway will carry this?
```

`ip route get` answers "is my traffic really going where I think?"
